Tua Hecyra takes its name from the fact that its plot turns upon the misunderstanding between a mother and daughter-inlaw. Colman has translated the word ‘stepmother3’ but lxvpd is etymologically, and in meaning, the same word as ‘socrus' amotherinlaw, and thera is the same close connexion between the correlative wbrds vods and ‘nunna’ a daughter-in·law. . The story of the play is as follows: A young man named Pamphilus, son cf Laches and Sostrata, used to keep company with one Bacchis. One night aa he was going to her house, rather the worse for wine, he met Philumena, the daughter of Phidippus and Myrrhina, on the road, and offered her violence, both of them being ignorant who the other was. She could not get any thing from him which could serve as a clue to his recog· nition; but be in the struggle managed to tear from ber finger a ring, which he carried to Bacchis aud gave to her. A short time after this he was married3 for his father was very anxious to break off his intimacy with Bacchis, and to see his son quietly settled down, that he might have some prospect of domestic comfort in his old age; and be never let hia son have any peace till he consented to take to himself a wife. Bya strange coincidence the wife selected for him was this very Philumena, whom he had met at night on bis way to his mistress's house; and her mother was only too glad to bave her married, hoping that she would be saved from public disgrace. But things did not turn cut as smoothly as she ex· pected; for Pamphilus did not at first shake off bis old love, but con· tinued to visit Bacchis every day, and totally avoided the company of his wife. Gradually, however, a change took place. Bacchis, being annoyed at the marriage of Pamphilus, behaved with great coldness and caprice towards him. Philumena, on the other hand, bore his neglect with the greatest patience and good temper. And so it came about that Pamphilus abandoned Bacchis altogether, and became devotedly attached to his wife. At this moment a relation of bis father's dies at Imbros, and Pamphilus is despatched to the spot to look after his property, his
